40|$|The waves {{propagation}} in the anisotropic {{media with}} single-sheeted hyperboloid dispersion relation is investigated. It is {{shown that the}} single-sheeted hyperboloid dispersion relation is an exact solution of Maxwell equations. E- (or H-) <b>polarized</b> <b>waves</b> are positively refracted whereas H- (or E-) <b>polarized</b> <b>waves</b> are negatively refracted at the interface associated with such anisotropic media. It is found that there dose not exist optical axis in the anisotropic media with single-sheeted hyperboloid dispersion if the permittivity and permeability tensors are diagonalizable simultaneously...|$|R
30|$|Large {{differences}} in ULF wave characteristics, such as occurrence frequency, polarization, and propagation direction, {{on either side}} of noon have been observed before both at high and low latitudes on the ground and in space (e.g., Kokubun, 1985; Kokubun et al., 1989; Anderson et al., 1990; Ziesolleck and McDiarmid, 1994, 1995; Chisham and Orr, 1997; Baker et al., 2003). The characteristics of afternoon sector Pc 5 waves are markedly different from those observed in the morning sector. Satellite observations (Kokubun et al., 1989; Anderson et al., 1990) show that they are predominantly a mixture of compressional and radially <b>polarized</b> <b>waves</b> and that the radially <b>polarized</b> <b>waves</b> have a poor ground correlation. These radially <b>polarized</b> <b>waves</b> are likely to be driven by westward drifting ions from the nightside of the magnetosphere (Southwood, 1976) and will usually have large azimuthal wave numbers m ~ 100.|$|R
5000|$|Vivaldi antennas can be {{made for}} linear <b>polarized</b> <b>waves</b> or - using two devices {{arranged}} in orthogonal direction - for transmitting / receiving both polarization orientations.|$|R
40|$|Publicación ISIIt {{is shown}} {{that in a}} plasma {{composed}} by electrons, a proton core, and a proton beam propagating along an external magnetic field, finite amplitude left-hand <b>polarized</b> <b>waves</b> propagating backward relative to the beam direction can trigger nonlinear ion-acoustic waves supported by the beam. A detailed study of such instabilities is carried out. The instability bounds are such that if there are large amplitude left-hand <b>polarized</b> <b>waves</b> propagating toward the Sun, nonlinear ion-acoustic waves supported by the beam should exist in high-speed solar wind streams...|$|R
